title: For Sale:  Romanian AK47 SAR-1 For Sale w/4 30rd Mags
postcontent: I am selling my Romanian AK-47 SAR-1 to pay for an HK Expert 40, otherwise I would keep this gun, but having several other match grade semi-autos rifles in a stupid accurate calibers like 6.5 Grendel and 204 Ruger, I just don't shoot this AK very often.  Unlike the WASR-10 models , this has the dimpled magazine well designed to hold hi-cap magazines tightly.  The SAR-1s were assembled in the US from Romanian and US parts to be rule 922R compliant, they do not have a bayonet lug and the barrel isn't threaded (have a gunsmith thread it if you really want, it isn't difficult.)  Designed for hi-cap magazines (not dremeled out like the WASR-10s) these models aren't very picky about ammo and will feed pretty much any 7.62x39 from double stack magazines.  This gun has been a safe queen and my gunsmith put a brand new gas cylinder in it before Thanksgiving, because when he was going over it he thought it could cycle more smoothly.  I am pretty selective with my guns, even the non-high end ones and I always keep them clean and use Clenzoil.  I have shot 200 rounds or less through this gun since I purchased it approx. 15 years ago.  The sights are fine and the gun really isn't broken in yet.  If you want a reasonably priced AK-47 to shoot good groups (by AK standards) and you want one that will feed pretty much any ammo, this is the one to get.  The magazines aren't plastic, but all metal (better when you use the magazine as a fore grip during rapid fire shooting IMO) and two I have never used and are still coated with Cosmoline.  If you want ammo with the gun, I'll sell you surplus Wolf 7.62 x 39 123gr at $7 per 20rd box for up to 700 rounds or whatever amount I have left in 7.62x39.   800 obo

title: For Trade:  Polytech M14S/M1A 7.62 Battle Rifle w/ forged receiver & bolt, 20 rd mags, optics rail
postcontent:
This is a Polytech M14S Battle Rifle. Polytech used high quality forged receivers like the US Government originals, not the softer cast type used by many companies. A Fulton Armory Hardened bolt was added very recently for added strength and durability. It has a removable receiver mounted  Return-to-Zero Gen 3 optics rail. It has fully adjustable combat sights(some of the best ever put on a combat rifle), a chrome lined barrel that protects it from wear and corrosion, and is very difficult to find on newer M1A's. It also has a removable full cage flash hider and 6 (all in great shape) steel box type 20 round magazines that you can probably kiss goodbye soon.  

The M14/M1A uses the 7.62X51 (308 winchester) which is devastating up close or long range. 800 meters is a reasonable shot for and M1A. The Polytech receiver will work great with a short scout barrel (even better then the Springfield model). Or keep the original barrel, it has tight groups at 200 to 300 meters (with iron sights) and passes on the head space. This rifle will take USGI parts and upgrades, and the M1A is more then likely not getting banned so the parts will be there. Its a hell of a lot more durable then an AR (of any brand) and almost as accurite. And puts AK's to shame, more power, hell of a lot more range, better parts, better duriblity. And if it does jam with dirt and mud just jam the charging handle against the nearest thing because your not going to break it, dent it, or bend it.
